    AI Overview
    JSONL is a format where each line is a valid, independent JSON object, making it ideal for streaming and large datasets because it can be processed one line at a time. In contrast, standard JSON files contain a single, structured JSON object or array, requiring the entire file to be parsed at once, which can be memory-intensive for large files. The key difference is that JSONL uses newline characters to separate objects, while JSON uses commas and square brackets to structure a single array or object. 
    This video demonstrates how to compare JSON and JSONL files in Python:
    57s
    Lynn G. Kwong
    YouTube 29 Oct 2024
    Feature JSONJSONL (JSON Lines)
    StructureA single JSON object or an array of objects.A sequence of valid JSON objects, with each object on a new line.
    SeparatorsUses commas to separate elements within an array or object.Uses a newline character (\n) to separate objects.
    ParsingRequires the entire file to be loaded and parsed into memory.Can be processed line-by-line, making it memory-efficient for large files.
    Best forAPI responses, configuration files, nested data structures, and smaller datasets.Log files, streaming data, large datasets, and training machine learning models.
    Example[{"id": 1}, {"id": 2}]{"id": 1}\n{"id": 2}

    What is the difference between JSON and Jsonc?
    Jsonc is a simplified json format which allows comments and unquoted values delimited by whitespace. A jsonc formatted file can be transformed to a json file. Comments will be stripped out and quotes added. Any valid json is also a valid jsonc - but this goes only in one direction.
